Using with Nikon D7500, Samsung Tab A, and tether cable (sometimes WiFi). Works great with the D7500. To connect with WiFi you will need Firmware 1.10 installed on the D7500. I bought this app to have a live view while shooting videos for YouTube, etc. It allows me to control the camera remotely. I wanted to be able to check focus, exposure and start capture. It works very well for this purpose. Most features of the menus are exposed on the app screen and live view is clear. The manual focus controls are worth the price of the app alone. I like to shoot with a fairly wide aperture and this allows me dial in focus so both of us are within the acceptable focus zone. It's convenient to be able to set the ISO and aperture to get the best exposure setting without having to get behind the camera. Connecting with Wifi: You don not need to run Snapbridge. On the camera, press establish Wifi Connection. On your tablet or phone connect to the Wifi network displayed on the camera. In qDSLRDashboard, click the Wifi button labeled Nikon. Easy. Again you need firmware 1.10.

Congratulations on a great app.  Nikon D3300 and Samsung S5 paired through wireless.  Live View worked fine.  All functions (like ISO, WB, aperture, speed, focus) were controllable through the app.  The app can display D3300 NEF.  Remember to enable the wireless adapter on the phone after inserting the WU-1a, then pair the phone through wifi BEFORE opening the app.  It can take a while (about 60 seconds) to connect the app to the phone initially, but once connected it works a treat.  I am happy to pay $12 for this app.  The writer has done a great job.  Addendum: I just discovered that if WMU (Nikon Wireless Mobile Utility) is open, it blocks qDSLRDashboard from controlling the camera.  Close WMU before opening qDSLR.
